            <fr:title text="How to Make a Map">How to Make a Map</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Suppose we are working in a <fr:link href="/forest/0003/" title="Elementary Vector Space" uri="https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0003/" display-uri="0003" type="local">4-dimensional real vector space</fr:link>, we can choose our basis vectors and label them as,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[e_\mu \in  \mathbb {V},\ \mu =0,1,2,3]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>Any vectors belonging to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex> can now be written as,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\vec {A}=A^\mu  e_\mu ]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {W}]]></fr:tex> is a vector space with potentially a different dimensionality. We can choose to define a linear map which takes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {W}]]></fr:tex>,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\Lambda :\mathbb {V}\rightarrow \mathbb {W}]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>Here we use the notation,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\Braket {\Lambda ,v}\rightarrow  w]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>Suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {W}]]></fr:tex> has basis vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f_\alpha ]]></fr:tex>. To understand how the map applies to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex> we need to know how each of the basis vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_\mu ]]></fr:tex> transforms in the map,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\braket {\Lambda , e_\mu }=C_\mu {}^\alpha  f_\alpha ]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>A linear map has the property,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\braket {\Lambda , av_1+bv_2}=a\braket {\Lambda ,v_1}+b\braket {\Lambda ,v_2}]]></fr:tex>
            <html:p>The fact that the maps are linear means that given that we know how the basis vectors transform, we know how any vector in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex> space maps to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {W}]]></fr:tex>,</html:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\braket {\Lambda , A^\mu  e_\mu }=A^\mu \braket {\Lambda ,e_\mu }=A^\mu  C_\mu {}^\alpha  f_\alpha ]]></fr:tex>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>9</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://andrewczezowski.github.io/forest/0003/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>0003</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/0003/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Elementary Vector Space">Elementary Vector Space</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A vector is an element of a set called a vector space. We denote this set with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>Not every set is a vector space so we need properties which define a set as a vector space.</html:p>
            <html:ol><html:li><html:p><html:strong>Vector addition</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>The addition of two elements of a vector space will also belong to the vector space.</html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall  v,w \in  \mathbb {V} : v+w=s\in  \mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex></html:li>

<html:li><html:p><html:strong>Scalar Multiplication</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>The operation of multiplying an element of the vector space by a scalar will yield another vector in the space.</html:p>
  <html:p>Real vector spaces are characterized by only having members with scalar multiplication my the set of real numbers. Similarly, for complex vector spaces</html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall \ v\in  \mathbb {V} \land  a\in \mathbb {C} : av\in  \mathbb {V}]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>Linearity</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>In the context of a complex vector space.</html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall \ v, w\in  \mathbb {V} \land  a\in \mathbb {C}\rightarrow  a(v+w)=av+aw]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>The Null Vector</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>Every vector space must contain the null vector. Additionally, every vector has its opposite.</html:p>
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\forall \;v\in  \mathbb {V}, \exists \;w\in  \mathbb {V}\;|\;w=-v\; \land  v-v=0]]></fr:tex></html:li>
<html:li><html:p><html:strong>Dimensionality</html:strong></html:p>
  <html:p>The minimum number of vectors that could possibly describe any vector in that space. In other words the number of basis vectors. Dimensionality can be infinite.</html:p></html:li></html:ol>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
